% v2-final conclusion. n=100 numbers landed: pull > intercept > no_coord.
% Reframed around the pull-channel generalization story with intercept
% as the (negative) architectural alternative we tested honestly.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

ET-MCP names a coordination primitive for multi-agent LLM systems:
typed events biased toward negative knowledge, task-scoped, addressed
through an MCP-conformant transport.  We instantiate two reader-side
architectures over the same store and run the first controlled
head-to-head under matched payload: \emph{pull} (agent-as-reader, via
a curated peer-warnings summary at trial start) and \emph{intercept}
(framework-as-reader, via a \texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block prepended
to a tool's response when the call's (name, arguments) match a peer
event from a prior failed trial).  On $\tau^2$-bench retail at
$n{=}100$ tasks (600 trials, Claude Haiku~4.5), pull significantly
dominates intercept: $9$ task-level wins against $27$ losses on
pass$^1$ (sign test $p{=}0.004$, Cliff's $\delta{=}+0.18$;
$7$ vs.\ $18$ on pass$^2$, $p{=}0.043$).  Pull also lifts
pass$^1$ by $+8$\,pp and pass$^2$ by $+6$\,pp over no-coordination
(directional, $p{=}0.18$ and $p{=}0.36$); intercept underperforms
no-coordination by $-10$\,pp and $-5$\,pp.  Within-system evidence
from the 810-trial TravelPlanner factorial corroborates the
mechanism: holding the negative-knowledge payload constant, the pull
channel architecturally outperforms structured push baselines
($3.9\%$ vs.\ $5.2\%$ redundancy, Wilcoxon-significant).  The within-
system pull-channel claim generalizes to a Sierra-published peer-
reviewed benchmark at the public-protocol level.

The architectural lesson is the v2 contribution and runs counter to
the production-stack intuition.  Production multi-agent runtimes
expose framework-level tool-call interception as a primitive
(Strands hooks~\cite{strandshooks2025}, AgentCore
Policy~\cite{agentcorepolicy2025}, LangChain
middleware~\cite{langchainmiddleware2026}, Microsoft Agent
Framework~\cite{msagentframework2026}); these mechanisms are
deployed today for blocking, validation, retries, and caching, and
the industry trend points toward more framework mediation.  Our
finding is that the same hook surface, repurposed to inject
coordination warnings on every matching tool call, \emph{harms}
the headline metric---intercept fires a mean of $2.8$ warnings per
trial and the agent cannot weigh them globally against the current
state.  The agent's single-summary read at trial start carries more
useful signal than the framework's blind per-call injection.
Selective agent-mediated reading, not framework-side blind
injection, is the architecturally superior choice for coordination
semantics, at the scale and model we test.  Coordination is not
symmetric with blocking.

We additionally release a $\sim$700-line Anthropic-native
$\tau^2$-bench harness that mitigates a documented bug class in
$\tau^2$-bench's bundled litellm-based pipeline (consistent with
multiple open issues~\cite{litellmissue12404,litellmissue15322}).
Zero infra errors at 600 trials.  We expect this measurement
infrastructure to be useful to other groups reproducing or extending
$\tau$-bench-family claims on Anthropic deployments---the workshop
theme of post-deployment trust controls applies to the benchmark
itself as much as to the systems it measures.

Several directions remain open.  The writer-side selection policy
(currently the last $k{=}3$ tool calls of any failed trial) is a
hand-tuned causal-attribution heuristic; a learned attribution policy
would likely tighten both pull and intercept.  The intercept finding
may invert under a more selective framework-side filter that
suppresses redundant warnings within a single trial---we tested the
naive ``fire on every match'' design as the apples-to-apples
contrast against pull's single-summary read, and a smarter
framework reader would be a separate study.  Pass$^k$ at $k{>}2$
would let us measure whether the architectural gap widens with
retry budget.  The head-to-head should be repeated on the other
$\tau^2$ domains (airline, telecom) and on stronger models
(Sonnet, Opus) once the harness's domain-bridging layer is
generalized.  We release the code, harness, and trial-level data to
make these follow-ups straightforward.
